The United States economy has experienced 94 consecutive months of positive job growth, with 3.9 million jobs created since President Donald J. Trump was elected in November 2016. While the job growth in July fell short of expectations, the average monthly job growth for 2018 is 215,000, surpassing the averages for 2016 and 2017. Industries such as manufacturing and professional & business services have seen significant gains in job growth. The unemployment rate has decreased to 3.9 percent, the lowest it has been since January 2000. Additionally, the unemployment rate for Hispanics has reached a historic low of 4.5 percent. The employment-population ratio has also increased, indicating more people are finding jobs. Overall, the report suggests that the American labor market is thriving under the Trump Administration's pro-growth policies.